{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539702"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.02,0.01,0.04,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1314"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4150"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting termination of pregnancy. Her last menstrual period was 12 weeks ago, and a urine pregnancy test is positive. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is in a stable relationship and has carefully considered her options. She is open to either medical or surgical termination and is happy to be guided by the recommendation of the treating team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a soft, non-tender abdomen. A transvaginal ultrasound confirms an intrauterine pregnancy with a CRL consistent with 12+5 weeks gestation and a FHR 155bpm. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange outpatient medical termination with mifepristone","Recommend continuing the pregnancy","Repeat ultrasound in one week","Refer for psychological counselling","Explain need for surgical termination"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents requesting termination of pregnancy at 12 weeks gestation. However, outpatient medical termination is not recommended beyond 9 weeks gestation due to increased risks of incomplete abortion and heavy bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplain need for surgical termination\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. The patient should be counselled that surgical management is the safer and more appropriate option at this gestation, with a high success rate and predictable course. Blood group testing would then be arranged prior to the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange outpatient medical termination with mifepristone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this gestation as it is associated with higher complication rates and lower success rates compared to surgical management after 9 weeks. If the patient had a strong preference for medical management this would likely need management in a inpatient hospital setting \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend continuing the pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E would not respect the patient\u0027s autonomy and right to choose termination of pregnancy. The role of the healthcare provider is to provide evidence-based options and support informed decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for psychological counselling\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the patient appears to have made an informed decision. While counselling should always be available, it should not be mandatory when a patient has clearly expressed their wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the current scan has already confirmed an intrauterine pregnancy with clear dating. Further delay would not provide additional useful information and may push the pregnancy beyond preferred gestational age limits for some procedures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical termination of pregnancy is not recommended beyond 9 weeks gestation due to increased risk of complications.","Surgical termination is the preferred method for pregnancies between 9-14 weeks gestation.","Pre-operative blood group testing is essential to identify women requiring anti-D immunoglobulin."],"references":["Queensland Clinical Guidelines. Termination of pregnancy [Internet]. Brisbane: Queensland Health; 2024 Sep. Report No.: MN24.21-V10-R29. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0029/735293/g-top.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91911"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-22T12:32:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-22T14:46:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109538"}}},"meta":{"